<https://w3id.org/mqto#IshikawaItem> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Abstract superclass for the three categories of root causes in an Ishikawa (fishbone) diagram: Machine, Material, and Method. Domain-specific ontologies can specialize these concepts for their manufacturing domain."@en .
<https://w3id.org/mqto#IshikawaItem> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Ishikawa Item"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/mqto#List
<https://w3id.org/mqto#List> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/mqto#List> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "An ordered, reusable container of CountermeasureSteps within the specified layer. Implements an OWL-native linked list pattern (mqto:first / mqto:rest) inspired by RDF Collections, but using explicit OWL class and property definitions for better reasoner compatibility. Standard rdf:List creates known issues with OWL reasoners due to blank node handling and recursive structure reasoning. This approach ensures compatibility with standard reasoners such as HermiT and Pellet while maintaining the core benefit: step order is external to the step instances, allowing steps to be shared across different Countermeasure procedures without embedding ordering information in the steps themselves. The list is terminated by mqto:nil. See OWL 2 Primer Section 4.2 on structural specification limitations with blank nodes."@en .
<https://w3id.org/mqto#List> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "List"@en .
<https://w3id.org/mqto#List> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> <http://www.w3.org/TR/owl2-primer/> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/mqto#Machine
